   =20
      Bad bankruptcy
   =20
 =20
The Sackler family owns Purdue Pharma LP, a drug company that produces the =
opioid painkiller=C2=A0OxyContin, which helped spark an=C2=A0epidemic of op=
ioid addiction. The Sacklers got very rich from OxyContin. A lot of people =
have sued Purdue, and the Sacklers, for their actions and for various harms=
 done by the opioid crisis. (These people include families of victims of ad=
diction, hospitals,=C2=A0state attorneys general, =E2=80=9Ceven representat=
ives of unborn children who were destined to suffer from opioid addiction.=
=E2=80=9D[1]) There are hundreds of thousands of=C2=A0claims, and the=C2=A0=
damages asserted are in the trillions of dollars, vastly exceeding the valu=
e of Purdue Pharma and the combined wealth of the Sacklers.[2]=C2=A0So Purd=
ue filed for bankruptcy. When it filed for bankruptcy it had plenty of mone=
y and no debt. The bankruptcy was purely preemptive. The point was not that=
 Purdue was out of money; the point was that there were=C2=A0so many=C2=A0l=
awsuits that it needed some fair way to deal with them. If you have a trill=
ion dollars of lawsuits and a few billion dollars of assets, and you lose t=
he first few lawsuits, you=E2=80=99ll pay out all your money to those first=
 few plaintiffs and have nothing left over for anyone else. So you file for=
 bankruptcy to work out all the lawsuits =E2=80=94=C2=A0in bankruptcy they =
are called =E2=80=9Cclaims=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0at once. Purdue did that=
, and there were years of negotiations and mediation, costing hundreds of m=
illions of dollars in professional fees, and they worked out a deal =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Cplan of reorganization,=E2=80=9D in bankruptcy language=
 =E2=80=94 that was acceptable to a large majority of the creditors (the pe=
ople with the claims).In general the way corporate bankruptcy works in the =
U.S. is=C2=A0not=C2=A0that the company liquidates, sells all its stuff, and=
 splits the cash among=C2=A0the creditors. In general the way it works is t=
hat the company continues as a going concern to maximize its value, but=C2=
=A0now the creditors own it.  This is a weird outcome when the company went=
 bankrupt because its product harmed people and the people who were harmed =
are the creditors. You were harmed by the opioid epidemic, and to make it u=
p to you,=C2=A0now you own an opioid company.And that is in fact part of th=
e deal here: Under the plan, Purdue will be renamed =E2=80=9CKnoa Pharma,=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and it will =E2=80=9Cbe governed by a board of five or seven=
 disinterested and independent managers initially selected=E2=80=9D by some=
 of the creditors, specifically by committees=C2=A0of government creditors =
(states, cities, counties, hospital districts, etc.).[3] Knoa will continue=
 to operate, and =E2=80=9Cwill manufacture products, including Betadine, De=
nokot, Colace, magnesium products, opioids and opioid-abatement medications=
, and oncology therapies.=E2=80=9D Its profits will go into trusts for the =
various creditors. The managers will try to sell off its assets by the end =
of 2024, to generate more cash for those creditors. In the meantime Knoa wi=
ll sell opioids on behalf of opioid victims, but this time more carefully:[=
Knoa] will continue [Purdue=E2=80=99s]=C2=A0development of opioid overdose =
reversal and addiction treatment medications, and it must deliver millions =
of doses of those medications at low or no cost when development is complet=
e (these will be distributed to groups or entities to be determined post-em=
ergence). [Knoa]=C2=A0will be subject to an =E2=80=9COperating Injunction=
=E2=80=9D that prohibits it from, among other things, promoting opioid prod=
ucts and providing financial incentives to its sales and marketing employee=
s that are =E2=80=9Cdirectly=E2=80=9D (but not indirectly) based on sales v=
olumes or sales quotas for opioid products. It also is subject to =E2=80=9C=
Governance Covenants=E2=80=9D that ensure that [Knoa] provides all its prod=
ucts in a =E2=80=9Csafe manner,=E2=80=9D complies with settlement obligatio=
ns, pursues public health initiatives, and follows pharmaceutical best prac=
tices.=C2=A0The cash generated by running and then selling Knoa will go to =
the creditors, including both private claimants (victims, families, etc.), =
who will get money damages, and government claimants, who will get money th=
at they can use =E2=80=9Cto abate the opioid crisis.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The nego=
tiated bankruptcy plan determines how this money will be split among all th=
e different sorts of creditors.It is not, however, enough. The value of Pur=
due/Knoa is perhaps a couple of billion dollars, several orders of magnitud=
e less than the claims against it.=C2=A0As a general matter, this is someti=
mes a thing that happens: Sometimes there is a company, and it makes a prod=
uct, and people like the product and buy it and it generates profits, and t=
hen the product turns out to do some huge harm, and the harm is many times =
greater than the profits, and someone else bears the loss. The company=E2=
=80=99s existence was a net negative: It generated some good and much more =
bad, and handing the good parts of the company over to the victims of the b=
ad stuff cannot come close to compensating them.[4]But there is also a more=
 specific problem here, which is that the Sackler family extracted many bil=
lions of dollars of profits from Purdue over the years in the form of divid=
ends, and if they hand over Purdue to its creditors (1) the creditors will =
not get very much out of it but (2) the Sacklers will remain very rich.As a=
 general matter this too is something that just happens sometimes: Sharehol=
ders of corporations have limited liability,[5] and if the corporation goes=
 bust its creditors can=E2=80=99t generally come after the shareholders for=
 its debts. There are exceptions, though, and a lot of them seem to apply h=
ere. There are rules about =E2=80=9Cfraudulent transfer,=E2=80=9D saying es=
sentially that if a company is insolvent and pays out money to shareholders=
, they have to give the money back; arguably that applies to some or all of=
 the Sacklers=E2=80=99 dividends in recent years. Also many members of the =
Sackler family were, over the years, directors or officers of Purdue; its c=
reditors can sue them for various failings (violations of fiduciary duty) a=
s directors and officers. Also many states have laws that impose direct per=
sonal liability on directors or officers for various sorts of corporate mal=
feasance (fraud, unfair trade practices, etc.).In principle these questions=
=C2=A0too could be resolved by=C2=A0all the Sacklers=C2=A0filing for bankru=
ptcy. If their liability exceeded their assets, the court would let them ke=
ep enough money to live on and then divide the rest of their money among cr=
editors in a fair way. In practice this is not a viable solution, for two r=
easons. One is that the Sacklers have very little incentive to file for ban=
kruptcy and give up all their money until they=E2=80=99ve actually lost som=
e lawsuits, so you=E2=80=99d have to bring the lawsuits, and win them (and =
you might not), and then you=E2=80=99d have the problem of some creditors g=
etting ahead=C2=A0of other creditors, etc.; all the=C2=A0coordination=C2=A0=
and=C2=A0fairness=C2=A0benefits of the corporate bankruptcy are harder to a=
chieve in a personal bankruptcy.[6]Also though the Sacklers have just done =
a good job of hiding their money where a bankruptcy court can=E2=80=99t get=
 it. That=E2=80=99s, uh, perhaps societally non-optimal but nonetheless tru=
e:The Sacklers upstreaming some $10.4 billion out of the company between 20=
08 and 2017, which, according to their own expert, substantially reduced Pu=
rdue=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Csolvency cushion.=E2=80=9D Over half of that money =
was either invested in offshore companies owned by the Sacklers or deposite=
d into spendthrift trusts that could not be reached in bankruptcy and off-s=
hore entities located in places like the Bailiwick of Jersey. ...The assets=
 of family members are held principally in purportedly=C2=A0spendthrift tru=
sts located in the United States and offshore =E2=80=93 many of them on the=
 Bailiwick of Jersey =E2=80=93 and many of those assets cannot readily be l=
iquidated. As Judge Drain correctly observed, spendthrift trusts can and of=
ten do insulate assets from the bankruptcy process. And while generally app=
licable law governing U.S. trusts allows those trusts to be invaded when th=
ey are funded by fraudulent conveyances, there is a substantial question wh=
ether the same is true under Jersey law. Additionally, he noted that many S=
ackler family members live abroad, raising a barrier to an American court=
=E2=80=99s acquiring personal jurisdiction over them.=C2=A0So the legal sys=
tem might not be able to get at the bulk of the Sacklers=E2=80=99 money to =
give to the creditors.Still that doesn=E2=80=99t leave the creditors, or th=
e legal system, powerless. There are hundreds of thousands of potential law=
suits. It would be very unpleasant for the Sacklers to have to defend all o=
f them. There=E2=80=99s a decent chance they=E2=80=99d lose some and have t=
o file for bankruptcy and fight over the money in these offshore trusts; th=
ey might very well win and keep the money, but there=E2=80=99s some risk, a=
nd anyway filing for bankruptcy isn=E2=80=99t very nice. The Sacklers=C2=A0=
who live abroad, =E2=80=9Craising a barrier to an American court=E2=80=99s =
acquiring personal jurisdiction over them,=E2=80=9D would have to=C2=A0stay=
=C2=A0abroad to continue avoiding lawsuits.=C2=A0Basically the creditors do=
n=E2=80=99t want to have to go after the Sacklers personally because it wil=
l be unpleasant and laborious and won=E2=80=99t generate that much money, b=
ut the Sacklers also don=E2=80=99t want to have the creditors come after th=
em personally, because it will be unpleasant and laborious and will cost th=
em a lot of money.So that leaves obvious=C2=A0room=C2=A0for settlement. The=
 Sacklers can agree to pay a lot of money, billions of dollars, much of the=
ir fortune but certainly not all of it, to the creditors in the Purdue bank=
ruptcy,=C2=A0in exchange for not being sued about Purdue matters. They can =
pay=C2=A0possibly much more than they=E2=80=99d have to pay if they were su=
ed and lost =E2=80=94 they can voluntarily pay over money that they have le=
gally shielded from U.S. courts =E2=80=94=C2=A0in exchange for not having t=
o go through the process of being sued and losing. This is a win for the cr=
editors, who (1) avoid the expense and uncertainty of litigation and (2) ge=
t more money, and a win for the Sacklers, who (1) avoid the unpleasantness =
of litigation and endless=C2=A0bad publicity and (2) still keep quite a lot=
 of money.=C2=A0And so that was the deal reached in the Purdue bankruptcy n=
egotiations. The Sacklers would contribute about $4.3 billion of cash to Pu=
rdue=E2=80=99s creditors, and in exchange they=E2=80=99d get a release from=
 all liability for Purdue=E2=80=99s actions:Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy was=
 thus a critical part of a strategy to secure for the Sacklers a release fr=
om any liability for past and even future opioid-related litigation without=
 having to pursue personal bankruptcy. David Sackler acknowledged as much i=
n his testimony, =E2=80=9CI don't know of=C2=A0another forum that would all=
ow this kind of global solution, this kind of equitable solution for allpar=
ties.=E2=80=9DBloomberg  reported in September:As part of the bankruptcy de=
al, the Sacklers will relinquish their equity in Purdue; as of 2019, there =
were no family members left on the board or in management positions. They w=
ill also contribute $4.325 billion in cash and forfeit control of family fo=
undations worth $175 million. =E2=80=A6In order to fund the bulk of the cas=
h payments =E2=80=94 and as part of the deal to exit the industry =E2=80=94=
 the Sacklers will agree to sell their international pharmaceutical holding=
s within seven years. That sale could generate something like $3 billion af=
ter taxes, according to asset statements provided to the court. The remaind=
er of the settlement will come out of the $8.7 billion in assets that the S=
acklers still control outside the drug industry.So in round numbers they ha=
ve $11.7 billion of assets and will pay $4.5 billion, keeping about $7 bill=
ion. Given the constraints of the legal system this is probably a good deal=
, and when it was put to a vote of creditors something=C2=A0like 95% of the=
m approved.[7]There is, however, a problem with it. The point of bankruptcy=
 is to take all of the claims against a debtor and deal with them once and =
for all in a fair way. But the Sacklers did not file for bankruptcy. And th=
e bankruptcy plan required dealing once and for all with a lot of claims=C2=
=A0against the Sacklers, and it=E2=80=99s not clear that a bankruptcy court=
 can do that. It is very clear why it would want to =E2=80=94=C2=A0to deal =
with those claims in an organized way=C2=A0and to maximize recovery for the=
 creditors =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s not clear that it can.[8] If, fo=
r instance, a state attorney general wants to sue a member of the Sackler f=
amily for violating state consumer protection laws, does the Purdue bankrup=
tcy court have the right to tell her not to?This sort of settlement is call=
ed a =E2=80=9Cthird-party release,=E2=80=9D and it is common but controvers=
ial; some U.S. courts have allowed third-party releases and some have not. =
The bankruptcy judge in the Purdue case allowed it, but some creditors =E2=
=80=94 particularly some state attorneys general =E2=80=94=C2=A0objected an=
d appealed to the district court. They were=C2=A0joined by the U.S. Departm=
ent of Justice in arguing that the bankruptcy code does not allow third-par=
ty releases. And last week they won, for now; U.S. District Judge Colleen M=
cMahon agreed with them and tossed out the Purdue bankruptcy plan. Here is =
her opinion, which I have been quoting here. Here's the conclusion:Aided by=
 superb briefing and argument on both sides of the question, and by extende=
d ruminations on the subject by several esteemed bankruptcy judges of our o=
wn District =E2=80=93 Judge Drain not the least =E2=80=93 this Court conclu=
des that the Bankruptcy Code does not authorize such nonconsensual non-debt=
or releases: not in its express text (which is conceded); not in its silenc=
e (which is disputed); and not in any section or sections of the Bankruptcy=
 Code that, read singly or together, purport to confer generalized or =E2=
=80=9Cresidual=E2=80=9D powers on a court sitting in bankruptcy.=C2=A0This =
strikes me as a reasonable reading of the bankruptcy code, though I am cert=
ainly not an expert. (There will definitely be an appeal.) It does seem lik=
e a bad outcome, though? The Wall Street Journal notes:After U.S. District =
Judge Colleen McMahon=E2=80=99s surprise ruling last week overturning a rou=
ghly $4.5 billion settlement between the OxyContin maker and members of the=
 Sackler family who own the company, Purdue, once on the verge of settling =
an onslaught of lawsuits over its flagship opioid painkiller, will remain i=
n bankruptcy court as it attempts to salvage a settlement that took years a=
nd hundreds of millions of dollars to craft.Instead of paying billions of d=
ollars to opioid victims and states, Purdue will stay in limbo and pay hund=
reds of millions of dollars to lawyers.As a matter of law this ruling might=
 be right. And of course it does seem unfair to cut off lawsuits against th=
e Sacklers; here is Bloomberg News from last week:Some members of Congress =
have proposed legislation to curb such practices. A bill backed by Dick Dur=
bin, the second-ranking Democrat in the U.S. Senate, would prevent owners o=
f a failed company from using bankruptcy to shield themselves from lawsuits=
.=E2=80=9CPurdue Pharma can go into bankruptcy and somehow we=E2=80=99re pr=
otecting the Sackler family=E2=80=99s personal assets from lawsuits? I just=
 think it=E2=80=99s fundamentally unfair,=E2=80=9D Durbin said in a telepho=
ne interview. =E2=80=9CTo think that they were not party to the bankruptcy =
and they=E2=80=99re receiving this favored treatment is fundamentally wrong=
.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The problem is ... well, one problem is that fairness is so=
metimes the enemy of pragmatism; letting the Sacklers keep billions and avo=
id litigation might be the only way to get them to=C2=A0pay=C2=A0billions:P=
urdue has vowed to appeal. But if the ruling stands, it would threaten to u=
pend long-practiced maneuvers allowing companies to shield executives and o=
wners -- and their cash -- as they slash debts in bankruptcy court. The rul=
ing comes at the end of a year in which lawmakers and state attorneys gener=
al have grown increasingly uneasy with such tactics, which they see as ramp=
ant abuse of the nation=E2=80=99s bankruptcy laws. ...The third-party relea=
ses granted to the Sacklers are a common piece of bankruptcy exit strategie=
s. They give people facing years of litigation an incentive to fork over ca=
sh to creditors in exchange for peace of mind. =E2=80=A6Insolvency advisers=
 worry that lawmakers will inadvertently hurt the people they=E2=80=99re tr=
ying to protect. Without strong incentives to settle, corporate wrongdoers =
may instead spend millions fighting lawsuits in state and federal court rat=
her than offering cash to victims, restructuring expert William A. Brandt, =
Jr. said.Also it is not at all clear that the bankruptcy plan=C2=A0is what =
is shielding the Sacklers=E2=80=99 personal assets. One=C2=A0reason the ban=
kruptcy plan released=C2=A0the Sacklers from liability, and the bankruptcy =
judge approved it, is that=C2=A0their assets were probably already shielded=
, in offshore spendthrift trusts that creditors probably couldn=E2=80=99t t=
ouch. That does seem bad! But getting rid of third-party releases in bankru=
ptcy doesn=E2=80=99t fix it.And note that the result of this ruling is not =
that they go back to the negotiating table and the Sacklers kick in, you kn=
ow, $8 billion instead of $4.5 billion. The result of this ruling is that t=
he whole settlement framework is illegal, and the bankruptcy court can=E2=
=80=99t cut off lawsuits against the Sacklers for any amount of money. That=
 can only happen if they file for bankruptcy themselves, in which case pres=
umably they=E2=80=99d=C2=A0fight to keep all their offshore trusts shielded=
 from bankruptcy.Opioid addiction is of course a huge societal problem in t=
he U.S. There are also the huge legal and economic problems of figuring out=
 who is financially responsible for the costs of that epidemic and who is e=
ntitled to financial compensation, and then making the responsible people p=
ay and channeling the money fairly to the people entitled to it. That is a =
big responsibility with enormous social consequences, and in the U.S. that =
sort of responsibility generally gets put on a bankruptcy court. These big =
social decisions about fairness and responsibility are made by a bankruptcy=
 judge, who has a ton of power and flexibility to try to craft the best pos=
sible solution. But not unlimited power, and perhaps not enough power.
