-fungible token, and why. I clicked this with horror, assuming that the rel=
ative prices of NFT series cannot be determined by any sort of fundamental =
analysis, and that the reason that Bored Apes and CryptoPunks had =E2=80=9C=
flipped=E2=80=9D would be some combination of =E2=80=9Cmore buyers than sel=
lers=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cpeople prefer looking at pictures of apes rather=
 than pictures of punks.=E2=80=9D NFTs are a way to capture and trade and m=
onetize certain specific types of online trendiness, and trends come and go=
 and whaddarya gonna do.But in fact the article is interesting, and there=
=C2=A0are=C2=A0fundamentals. I mean sure there is trendiness:Another recent=
 boost [for Bored Apes] has been their adoption by celebrities such as Jimm=
y Fallon, Steph Curry, and Post Malone. =E2=80=A6 Just yesterday, Snoop Dog=
g bought a Bored Ape, plus two mutant apes and a Bored Ape Kennel Cub (two =
of its offshoot projects) through MoonPay.But there is also a business of s=
orts, and the people who made Bored Apes seem to be better at obtaining tre=
ndiness than the people who made CryptoPunks: =E2=80=9CBAYC has a concierge=
 team onboarding celebrities to own apes versus Larvalabs, which is not doi=
ng much in that regard.=E2=80=9D In fashion, having publicists who get cele=
brities to wear your clothes is good for the brand; the same seems to be tr=
ue in NFTs.Also, though, cash flows:Over the last few months, the floor pri=
ce of CryptoPunks has fallen steadily, whereas that of BAYC NFTs has increa=
sed. There appear to be multiple factors at play."BAYC NFTs have generous I=
P rights compared to CryptoPunks," Bobby Ong, co-founder of CoinGecko and a=
n NFT expert, told The Block. "Some people are not happy that Larva Labs is=
 not assigning more rights."Put simply, CyptoPunk NFT owners do not get rig=
hts to use their NFTs for any commercial purpose, whereas BAYC NFT owners g=
et IP rights. Bored Ape owners are using these IP rights to build a blockch=
ain-based game in partnership with Animoca Brands.CryptoPunks and Bored Ape=
s are both NFTs pointing to digital images of characters (punks, apes). If =
you buy one, you get a certificate on a blockchain corresponding to a parti=
cular punk or ape. You can download a picture of your punk or ape to use as=
 your Twitter profile picture or whatever, but so can I; the NFT does not b=
y itself represent ownership in any traditional sense. If you buy a Bored A=
pe from the company that makes Bored Apes (or, now, in the secondary market=
), that company will=C2=A0also license some intellectual property rights to=
 you so that you can, I don=E2=80=99t know, sell T-shirts with your ape on =
it, or =E2=80=9Cbuild a blockchain-based game,=E2=80=9D sure. You =E2=80=9C=
own=E2=80=9D=C2=A0the ape image in some sense that approximates traditional=
 legal=C2=A0ownership of intellectual property. Meanwhile if you buy a Cryp=
toPunk from the company that makes CryptoPunks (or, now, in the secondary m=
arket), you get a much more limited license, and the company retains the co=
pyright and can commercialize the punks itself.We  talked the other day abo=
ut Non-Fungible Olive Gardens, a (parody) online community that allows peop=
le to basically pretend that they own Olive Garden franchises. Each token c=
orresponds to an individual Olive=C2=A0Garden in a purely hypothetical, jok=
ing way. This is how most NFTs work:=C2=A0You own the NFT, the NFT correspo=
nds to some online or offline thing, and=C2=A0you don=E2=80=99t own the thi=
ng. What I said about NFOGs is that this is a funny little pretend game, bu=
t that the interesting idea for NFTs is to try to make them correspond to r=
eal-world things:It does seem like the trading-digital-primitives part is p=
retty well established right now, but we are perhaps a bit stalled at the t=
ricky part of linking them to real-world assets. I can say words like =E2=
=80=9Cwe should put real estate title registries on the blockchain,=E2=80=
=9D but actually doing that requires getting lots of local jurisdictions an=
d courts and=C2=A0banks and mortgage companies and title insurers and real =
estate agents to coordinate around some particular blockchain solution; it =
is an enormous social=C2=A0coordination problem and seems=C2=A0exhausting.P=
utting intellectual-property rights on the blockchain is probably a bit eas=
ier than putting real estate on the blockchain. The apes aren=E2=80=99t exa=
ctly real-world assets, but it=E2=80=99s a start.
