<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bad bankruptcy</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Sackler family owns Purdue Pharma =
LP, a drug company that produces the opioid painkiller=C2=A0OxyContin, whic=
h helped spark an=C2=A0epidemic of opioid addiction. The Sacklers got very =
rich from OxyContin. A lot of people have sued Purdue, and the Sacklers, fo=
r their actions and for various harms done by the opioid crisis. (These peo=
ple include families of victims of addiction, hospitals,=C2=A0state attorne=
ys general, =E2=80=9Ceven representatives of unborn children who were desti=
ned to suffer from opioid addiction.=E2=80=9D[1]) There are hundreds of tho=
usands of=C2=A0claims, and the=C2=A0damages asserted are in the trillions o=
f dollars, vastly exceeding the value of Purdue Pharma and the combined wea=
lth of the Sacklers.[2]=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So Purdue fil=
ed for bankruptcy. When it filed for bankruptcy it had plenty of money and =
no debt. The bankruptcy was purely preemptive. The point was not that Purdu=
e was out of money; the point was that there were=C2=A0<em>so many=C2=A0</e=
m>lawsuits that it needed some fair way to deal with them. If you have a tr=
illion dollars of lawsuits and a few billion dollars of assets, and you los=
e the first few lawsuits, you=E2=80=99ll pay out all your money to those fi=
rst few plaintiffs and have nothing left over for anyone else. So you file =
for bankruptcy to work out all the lawsuits =E2=80=94=C2=A0in bankruptcy th=
ey are called =E2=80=9Cclaims=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0at once. Purdue did t=
hat, and there were years of negotiations and mediation, costing hundreds o=
f millions of dollars in professional fees, and they worked out a deal =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Cplan of reorganization,=E2=80=9D in bankruptcy langu=
age =E2=80=94 that was acceptable to a large majority of the creditors (the=
 people with the claims).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general the wa=
y corporate bankruptcy works in the U.S. is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>that the=
 company liquidates, sells all its stuff, and splits the cash among=C2=A0th=
e creditors. In general the way it works is that the company continues as a=
 going concern to maximize its value, but=C2=A0<em>now the creditors own it=
</em>. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26152179.28=
4656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDgtMj=
kvcHV0LXlvdXItYnVzaW5lc3MtaW4tYS1ib3g_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMzIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmd=
XRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjIzJnV0=
bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4406171e" itemprop=3D=
"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Th=
is is a weird outcome</a> when the company went bankrupt because its produc=
t harmed people and the people who were harmed are the creditors. You were =
harmed by the opioid epidemic, and to make it up to you,=C2=A0<em>now you o=
wn an opioid company</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And that is in f=
act part of the deal here: Under the plan, Purdue will be renamed =E2=80=9C=
Knoa Pharma,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0and it will =E2=80=9Cbe governed by a board of f=
ive or seven disinterested and independent managers initially selected=E2=
=80=9D by some of the creditors, specifically by committees=C2=A0of governm=
ent creditors (states, cities, counties, hospital districts, etc.).[3] Knoa=
 will continue to operate, and =E2=80=9Cwill manufacture products, includin=
g Betadine, Denokot, Colace, magnesium products, opioids and opioid-abateme=
nt medications, and oncology therapies.=E2=80=9D Its profits will go into t=
rusts for the various creditors. The managers will try to sell off its asse=
ts by the end of 2024, to generate more cash for those creditors. In the me=
antime Knoa will sell opioids on behalf of opioid victims, but this time mo=
re carefully:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[Knoa] will conti=
nue [Purdue=E2=80=99s]=C2=A0development of opioid overdose reversal and add=
iction treatment medications, and it must deliver millions of doses of thos=
e medications at low or no cost when development is complete (these will be=
 distributed to groups or entities to be determined post-emergence). [Knoa]=
=C2=A0will be subject to an =E2=80=9COperating Injunction=E2=80=9D that pro=
hibits it from, among other things, promoting opioid products and providing=
 financial incentives to its sales and marketing employees that are =E2=80=
=9Cdirectly=E2=80=9D (but not indirectly) based on sales volumes or sales q=
uotas for opioid products. It also is subject to =E2=80=9CGovernance Covena=
nts=E2=80=9D that ensure that [Knoa] provides all its products in a =E2=80=
=9Csafe manner,=E2=80=9D complies with settlement obligations, pursues publ=
ic health initiatives, and follows pharmaceutical best practices.=C2=A0</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The cash generated by running and=
 then selling Knoa will go to the creditors, including both private claiman=
ts (victims, families, etc.), who will get money damages, and government cl=
aimants, who will get money that they can use =E2=80=9Cto abate the opioid =
crisis.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The negotiated bankruptcy plan determines how this mo=
ney will be split among all the different sorts of creditors.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not, however, enough. The value of Purdue/Knoa i=
s perhaps a couple of billion dollars, several orders of magnitude less tha=
n the claims against it.=C2=A0<em>As a general matter</em>, this is sometim=
es a thing that happens: Sometimes there is a company, and it makes a produ=
ct, and people like the product and buy it and it generates profits, and th=
en the product turns out to do some huge harm, and the harm is many times g=
reater than the profits, and someone else bears the loss. The company=E2=80=
=99s existence was a net negative: It generated some good and much more bad=
, and handing the good parts of the company over to the victims of the bad =
stuff cannot come close to compensating them.[4]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">But there is also a more specific problem here, which is that the Sac=
kler family extracted many billions of dollars of profits from Purdue over =
the years in the form of dividends, and if they hand over Purdue to its cre=
ditors (1) the creditors will not get very much out of it but (2) the Sackl=
ers will remain very rich.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a general mat=
ter this too is something that just happens sometimes: Shareholders of corp=
orations have limited liability,[5] and if the corporation goes bust its cr=
editors can=E2=80=99t generally come after the shareholders for its debts. =
There are exceptions, though, and a lot of them seem to apply here. There a=
re rules about =E2=80=9Cfraudulent transfer,=E2=80=9D saying essentially th=
at if a company is insolvent and pays out money to shareholders, they have =
to give the money back; arguably that applies to some or all of the Sackler=
s=E2=80=99 dividends in recent years. Also many members of the Sackler fami=
ly were, over the years, directors or officers of Purdue; its creditors can=
 sue them for various failings (violations of fiduciary duty) as directors =
and officers. Also many states have laws that impose direct personal liabil=
ity on directors or officers for various sorts of corporate malfeasance (fr=
aud, unfair trade practices, etc.).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In prin=
ciple these questions=C2=A0too could be resolved by=C2=A0<em>all the Sackle=
rs=C2=A0</em>filing for bankruptcy. If their liability exceeded their asset=
s, the court would let them keep enough money to live on and then divide th=
e rest of their money among creditors in a fair way. In practice this is no=
t a viable solution, for two reasons. One is that the Sacklers have very li=
ttle incentive to file for bankruptcy and give up all their money until the=
y=E2=80=99ve actually lost some lawsuits, so you=E2=80=99d have to bring th=
e lawsuits, and win them (and you might not), and then you=E2=80=99d have t=
he problem of some creditors getting ahead=C2=A0of other creditors, etc.; a=
ll the=C2=A0<em>coordination=C2=A0</em>and=C2=A0<em>fairness=C2=A0</em>bene=
fits of the corporate bankruptcy are harder to achieve in a personal bankru=
ptcy.[6]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also though the Sacklers have just=
 done a good job of hiding their money where a bankruptcy court can=E2=80=
=99t get it. That=E2=80=99s, uh, perhaps societally non-optimal but nonethe=
less true:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Sacklers upstrea=
ming some $10.4 billion out of the company between 2008 and 2017, which, ac=
cording to their own expert, substantially reduced Purdue=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9Csolvency cushion.=E2=80=9D Over half of that money was either invested i=
n offshore companies owned by the Sacklers or deposited into spendthrift tr=
usts that could not be reached in bankruptcy and off-shore entities located=
 in places like the Bailiwick of Jersey. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">The assets of family members are held principally in purportedly=C2=A0spe=
ndthrift trusts located in the United States and offshore =E2=80=93 many of=
 them on the Bailiwick of Jersey =E2=80=93 and many of those assets cannot =
readily be liquidated. As Judge Drain correctly observed, spendthrift trust=
s can and often do insulate assets from the bankruptcy process. And while g=
enerally applicable law governing U.S. trusts allows those trusts to be inv=
aded when they are funded by fraudulent conveyances, there is a substantial=
 question whether the same is true under Jersey law. Additionally, he noted=
 that many Sackler family members live abroad, raising a barrier to an Amer=
ican court=E2=80=99s acquiring personal jurisdiction over them.=C2=A0</p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the legal system might not be ab=
le to get at the bulk of the Sacklers=E2=80=99 money to give to the credito=
rs.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still that doesn=E2=80=99t leave the cr=
editors, or the legal system, powerless. There are hundreds of thousands of=
 potential lawsuits. It would be very unpleasant for the Sacklers to have t=
o defend all of them. There=E2=80=99s a decent chance they=E2=80=99d lose s=
ome and have to file for bankruptcy and fight over the money in these offsh=
ore trusts; they might very well win and keep the money, but there=E2=80=99=
s some risk, and anyway filing for bankruptcy isn=E2=80=99t very nice. The =
Sacklers=C2=A0who live abroad, =E2=80=9Craising a barrier to an American co=
urt=E2=80=99s acquiring personal jurisdiction over them,=E2=80=9D would hav=
e to=C2=A0<em>stay=C2=A0</em>abroad to continue avoiding lawsuits.=C2=A0Bas=
ically the creditors don=E2=80=99t want to have to go after the Sacklers pe=
rsonally because it will be unpleasant and laborious and won=E2=80=99t gene=
rate that much money, but the Sacklers also don=E2=80=99t want to have the =
creditors come after them personally, because it will be unpleasant and lab=
orious and will cost them a lot of money.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">S=
o that leaves obvious=C2=A0room=C2=A0for settlement. The Sacklers can agree=
 to pay a lot of money, billions of dollars, much of their fortune but cert=
ainly not all of it, to the creditors in the Purdue bankruptcy,=C2=A0in exc=
hange for not being sued about Purdue matters. They can pay=C2=A0<em>possib=
ly much more than they=E2=80=99d have to pay if they were sued and lost </e=
m>=E2=80=94 they can voluntarily pay over money that they have legally shie=
lded from U.S. courts =E2=80=94=C2=A0in exchange for not having to go throu=
gh the process of being sued and losing. This is a win for the creditors, w=
ho (1) avoid the expense and uncertainty of litigation and (2) get more mon=
ey, and a win for the Sacklers, who (1) avoid the unpleasantness of litigat=
ion and endless=C2=A0bad publicity and (2) still keep quite a lot of money.=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so that was the deal reached in =
the Purdue bankruptcy negotiations. The Sacklers would contribute about $4.=
3 billion of cash to Purdue=E2=80=99s creditors, and in exchange they=E2=80=
=99d get a release from all liability for Purdue=E2=80=99s actions:</p><blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy was thus a=
 critical part of a strategy to secure for the Sacklers a release from any =
liability for past and even future opioid-related litigation without having=
 to pursue personal bankruptcy. David Sackler acknowledged as much in his t=
estimony, =E2=80=9CI don't know of=C2=A0another forum that would allow this=
 kind of global solution, this kind of equitable solution for all<br />part=
ies.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26152179.284656/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjEtMDktMDEvc2Fja2xlci1mYW1=
pbHktZXhpdHMtYmFua3J1cHRjeS10cmlhbC1vdmVyLXB1cmR1ZS1waGFybWEtcy1veHljb250aW=
4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMzIxX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjExMjIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB08cb6efa" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> reported in September</a>:</p><blockqu=
ote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As part of the bankruptcy deal, the Sackle=
rs will relinquish their equity in Purdue; as of 2019, there were no family=
 members left on the board or in management positions. They will also contr=
ibute $4.325 billion in cash and forfeit control of family foundations wort=
h $175 million. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In order to fund =
the bulk of the cash payments =E2=80=94 and as part of the deal to exit the=
 industry =E2=80=94 the Sacklers will agree to sell their international pha=
rmaceutical holdings within seven years. That sale could generate something=
 like $3 billion after taxes, according to asset statements provided to the=
 court. The remainder of the settlement will come out of the $8.7 billion i=
n assets that the Sacklers still control outside the drug industry.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So in round numbers they have $11.7 b=
illion of assets and will pay $4.5 billion, keeping about $7 billion. Given=
 the constraints of the legal system this is probably a good deal, and when=
 it was put to a vote of creditors something=C2=A0like 95% of them approved=
.[7]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is, however, a problem with it. =
The point of bankruptcy is to take all of the claims against a debtor and d=
eal with them once and for all in a fair way. But the Sacklers did not file=
 for bankruptcy. And the bankruptcy plan required dealing once and for all =
with a lot of claims=C2=A0<em>against the Sacklers</em>, and it=E2=80=99s n=
ot clear that a bankruptcy court can do that. It is very clear why it would=
 want to =E2=80=94=C2=A0to deal with those claims in an organized way=C2=A0=
and to maximize recovery for the creditors =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it=E2=80=99s =
not clear that it can.[8] If, for instance, a state attorney general wants =
to sue a member of the Sackler family for violating state consumer protecti=
on laws, does the Purdue bankruptcy court have the right to tell her not to=
?</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This sort of settlement is called a =E2=
=80=9Cthird-party release,=E2=80=9D and it is common but controversial; som=
e U.S. courts have allowed third-party releases and some have not. The bank=
ruptcy judge in the Purdue case allowed it, but some creditors =E2=80=94 pa=
rticularly some state attorneys general =E2=80=94=C2=A0objected and appeale=
d to the district court. They were=C2=A0joined by the U.S. Department of Ju=
stice in arguing that the bankruptcy code does not allow third-party releas=
es. And last week they won, for now; U.S. District Judge Colleen McMahon ag=
reed with them and tossed out the Purdue bankruptcy plan. Here is <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26152179.284656/aHR0cHM6L=
y9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JOTFlYelk0ZXhB=
Yy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB46b3ec13" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">her opinion</a>, which I=
 have been quoting here. Here's the conclusion:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">Aided by superb briefing and argument on both sides of the=
 question, and by extended ruminations on the subject by several esteemed b=
ankruptcy judges of our own District =E2=80=93 Judge Drain not the least =
=E2=80=93 this Court concludes that the Bankruptcy Code does not authorize =
such nonconsensual non-debtor releases: not in its express text (which is c=
onceded); not in its silence (which is disputed); and not in any section or=
 sections of the Bankruptcy Code that, read singly or together, purport to =
confer generalized or =E2=80=9Cresidual=E2=80=9D powers on a court sitting =
in bankruptcy.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This stri=
kes me as a reasonable reading of the bankruptcy code, though I am certainl=
y not an expert. (There will definitely be an appeal.) It does seem like a =
bad outcome, though? The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com=
/click/26152179.284656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9wdXJkdWUtcmVz=
dHJ1Y3R1cmluZy1vbi1ob2xkLWFmdGVyLWp1ZGdlLW92ZXJ0dXJucy1zZXR0bGVtZW50LTExNjQ=
wMTI0NDYyP21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXlhaG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd6b4a565" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">Wall Street Journal notes</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16p=
x 0;">After U.S. District Judge Colleen McMahon=E2=80=99s surprise ruling l=
ast week overturning a roughly $4.5 billion settlement between the OxyConti=
n maker and members of the Sackler family who own the company, Purdue, once=
 on the verge of settling an onslaught of lawsuits over its flagship opioid=
 painkiller, will remain in bankruptcy court as it attempts to salvage a se=
ttlement that took years and hundreds of millions of dollars to craft.</p><=
/blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead of paying billions of doll=
ars to opioid victims and states, Purdue will stay in limbo and pay hundred=
s of millions of dollars to lawyers.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As a m=
atter of law this ruling might be right. And of course it does seem unfair =
to cut off lawsuits against the Sacklers; here is <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26152179.284656/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
nLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMTcvc2Fja2xlci1ydWxpbmctdGhyZWF0ZW5zLW=
Nhc2gtZm9yLWltbXVuaXR5LWRlYWxzLWluLWJhbmtydXB0Y3k_Y21waWQ9QkJEMTIyMzIxX01PT=
kVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09=
MjExMjIzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd4710cf3"=
