</a> last week (citations omitted).</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><e=
m>[2] On page 47 of the opinion, Judge McMahon says =E2=80=9CJust 10% of th=
e claims so filed would give rise to over $140 trillion in aggregate liabil=
ity =E2=80=93 more than the whole world=E2=80=99s gross domestic product,=
=E2=80=9D though later (page 58) she notes that =E2=80=9Cover 618,000 claim=
s, in an amount exceeding two trillion dollars, had been filed in the bankr=
uptcy.=E2=80=9D For our purposes even one trillion dollars is astronomicall=
y more than the amount available to creditors, so it doesn=E2=80=99t really=
 matter how many trillions it is. O</em><em>n page 63 of the opinion Judge =
McMahon mentions =E2=80=9Cthe value of Purdue=E2=80=99s business as a going=
 concern ($1.8 billion)=E2=80=9D; the combined Sackler fortune seems to be =
in the $12 billion ballpark.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[3] S=
ee page 54. I=C2=A0don=E2=80=99t know where =E2=80=9CKnoa=E2=80=9D comes fr=
om.=C2=A0</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[4] Also makes it very a=
wkward to keep the company operating on behalf of the victims! I think the =
thinking here has to be something like=C2=A0=E2=80=9COxyContin, used proper=
ly, produces more good than bad, though Purdue=E2=80=99s actual practices o=
f marketing it produced much more bad than good =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that can=
 be fixed.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[5] Technicall=
y Purdue is a limited partnership but, again, limited liability.</em></p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[6] Also I say =E2=80=9Cthe Sacklers=E2=80=
=9D for simplicity but of course that refers to a lot of individuals with t=
heir own assets,=C2=A0different levels of responsibility for Purdue=E2=80=
=99s actions, different theories of liability, etc., which again makes fair=
ness and coordination hard.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[7] Pa=
ge 62: =E2=80=9CPurdue=E2=80=99s creditors overwhelmingly supported the set=
tlement. Some 120,000 votes were cast on the Plan =E2=80=93 a number far ex=
ceeding the voting in any other bankruptcy case. Over 95% of those voting i=
n the aggregate favored the Plan: over 79% of the states and territories su=
pported the Plan; over 96% of other governmental entities and tribes; and o=
ver 96% of the personal injury claimants; together with a supermajority of =
all other claimants.=E2=80=9D</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[8] =
There are two sorts of potential claims against the Sacklers. There are cla=
ims that *Purdue* might have against the Sacklers in bankruptcy. Fraudulent=
 conveyance and violations of fiduciary duty are claims that belong to Purd=
ue, and the bankruptcy court can definitely release those, because it is ad=
judicating Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy. But there are also what are called =
=E2=80=9Cdirect=E2=80=9D claims,=C2=A0e.g. state lawsuits against Purdue di=
rectors=C2=A0under consumer protection statutes. These are what is disputed=
 here. See page 94: =E2=80=9CFor these purposes, by derivative claims, I me=
an claims that would render the Sacklers liable because of Purdue=E2=80=99s=
 actions (which conduct may or may not have been committed because of the S=
acklers). =E2=80=98Derivative=E2=80=99 claims are those seek to recover fro=
m the estate indirectly =E2=80=98on the basis of [the debtor=E2=80=99s] con=
duct,=E2=80=99 as opposed to the non-debtor=E2=80=99s own conduct.=C2=A0Der=
ivative claims in every sense relate to the adjustment of the debtor-credit=
or relationship, because they are claims that relate to injury to the corpo=
ration itself. If the creditor=E2=80=99s claim is one that a bankruptcy tru=
stee could bring on behalf of the estate, then it is derivative.=C2=A0By di=
rect claims, I mean claims that are not derivative of Purdue=E2=80=99s liab=
ility, but are based on the Sacklers=E2=80=99 own, individual liability, pr=
edicated on their own alleged misconduct and the breach of duties owed to c=
laimants other than Purdue. =E2=80=98Direct=E2=80=99 claims are based upon =
a =E2=80=98particularized=E2=80=99 injury to a third party that can be dire=
ctly traced to a non-debtor=E2=80=99s conduct.=C2=A0 The release of claims =
against the Sacklers that are derivative of the estate=E2=80=99s claims the=
m is effected by Section 10.6(b) of the Plan, which is not attacked as bein=
g beyond the power of the Bankruptcy Court. The Section 10.7 Shareholder Re=
lease under attack is different. It releases all members of the Sackler fam=
ilies, as well as a variety of trusts, partnerships and corporations associ=
ated with the family and the people who run and advise those entities, from=
 liability for claims that have been brought against them personally by thi=
rd parties =E2=80=93=C2=A0claims that are not derivative, but as to=C2=A0wh=
ich Purdue=E2=80=99s conduct is a legally relevant factor.=E2=80=9D</em></p=
